nalysis and theory.Situated at the intersection of feminism, law, and economics, Feminism Confronts Homo Economicus will appeal to scholars and students of these disciplines as well as policy analysts and social theorists interested in family, education, labor, and welfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEconomic man. 0aFeminist jurisprudence. 0aLaw and economics. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 4aGender Studies. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh1 aAustin, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinig, Margaret F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Neil H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbone, June, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDougherty, Terence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDougherty, Terence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEngland, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErtman, Martha M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFineman, Martha Albertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFineman, Martha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKessler, Laura T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKysar, Douglas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaquer Estin, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLieberwitz, Risa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayes, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClain, Linda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca